      "help": "This node can be used to switch or dim a light. It can also be used to set the volume of a speaker or switch a socket. You can choose between \"dimmer state\" (sets the level to an predefined \"on\" level or \"off level\"), \"dimmer\" (dims a light) and \"switch\" (sets the state). If \"switching\" is selected by default there is one input. When set to <code>true</code> the selected output variable is set to <code>true</code>. When set to <code>false</code> the selected variable is set to <code>false</code>. \"2-channel input\" adds a second input. <code>true</code> on the first input switches the light or socket on. <code>true</code> on the second input switches it off. When \"2-channel input\" is selected <code>false</code> is ignored. \"Dimmer\" can be used to dim using a two-state input. <code>true</code> on input 2 or 3 starts the dimming process, <code>false</code> stops it. Input 1 can be used to set the selected output variable to <code>Value off</code> (<code>false</code>) or <code>Max. value</code> (<code>true</code>). <code>Min. value</code> is the minimum possible dim value (where the light is not flickering). <code>Min. step</code> is the minimum step the output variable value is incremented or decremented. <code>Interval</code> is the interval between dim steps. The shorter the interval the smoother the dimming operation. But be aware that not all devices support short time spans between setting values (especially wireless devices). <code>Factor</code> can be used to have larger dim steps for smaller values and smaller dim steps for larger values. The formula is: <code>currentValue +=/-= step + (factor * currentValue)</code>. So setting <code>factor</code> to <code>0</code> causes linear dimming.",
